{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# op-cert: remove the legacy HMAC scheme (contract phase) via expand-contract migration\n\n## Why\nOnce the producer signing seam ships (the expand phase: producers mint Ed25519 op-certs, the read\npath accepts both envelopes and legacy HMAC records), the HMAC scheme is dead weight for op-cert\nkinds — and leaving it verifiable keeps a forgeable path alive (anyone holding a clone's symmetric\nsecret can mint a \"certified\" verdict). This contract phase removes HMAC signing AND verification\nfor the op-cert kinds (`plan-review`, `completion-verifier`), completing the migration begun in\nthe foundation epic. The producer-key fork this story previously carried is settled in the epic's\n\"Producer-signing & compute-runtime design resolution\" (fork A: every environment signs locally\nwith its own Ed25519 key) — this story only removes the legacy path.\n\n**Hard dependency (not yet on `main`):** the producer signing seam story (the expand phase) and\nthe op-cert stack (Gerrit changes 649/650/660, in review) must land first — the asymmetric\nproducer path this story contracts onto does not exist on current `origin/main`; enforced by the\n`depends_on` link and the dependency-gate AC below.\n\n## What\n- Remove the HMAC registration for the op-cert kinds from `src/rebar/attest/hmac_legacy.py` /\n  `attest/registry.py` `POLICY` so neither `plan-review` nor `completion-verifier` resolves the\n  `HMAC-SHA256` scheme. Shared functions are enumerated explicitly — changed vs untouched:\n  - **changed**: `signing.sign_manifest` (the expand phase's dual-shape window closes: the HMAC\n    branch for op-cert kinds is deleted, envelope-only); `hmac_legacy` op-cert kind\n    registrations (deleted); the op-cert read path (HMAC records for these kinds no longer\n    verify); `sign_result.schema.json` tightened to envelope-only for these kinds.\n  - **untouched**: `signing.compute_signature` (generic HMAC utility), the `.signing-key`\n    genesis and its non-op-cert consumers (`rebar init` seeds it; generic manifest verify), and\n    the authorship kind. `.signing-key` removal is explicitly OUT of scope.\n- Read path post-contract: a pre-existing HMAC attestation reads as **not-certified** (validity is\n  computed on read) — it is preserved in the event log, never rewritten. Re-issue = re-run the\n  gate (`rebar review-plan` re-signs the current plan; re-closing re-earns the completion cert).\n- MCP surface: `sign_manifest` / `verify_signature` operate exclusively on the op-cert seam for\n  these kinds; their docs/help updated.\n- **Migration artifact** `docs/migrations/hmac-opcert-removal.md` (a named observable artifact):\n  `## Expand` (the producer-seam story: write-new/read-both) and `## Contract` (this story)\n  sections, the cutover procedure (upgrade order: reconcile hosts first, per the store rollout\n  rule — older clones preserve-and-ignore envelope events and `fsck` WARNs), the re-issue\n  procedure for still-live HMAC attestations, and the rollback posture (required-environment\n  policy is opt-in and defaults off; absent `.rebar/trusted_environments.yaml` /\n  `verify.require_environment` unset keeps low-security behavior).\n- No flag-day break: tickets whose HMAC attestation goes stale simply re-earn certs on their next\n  gate run; closed history is untouched.\n\n## Scope\n- In: HMAC removal for op-cert kinds, read-path contract behavior, the migration doc, MCP-surface\n  updates, tests below.\n- Out: the authorship kind (already asymmetric, identity epic); the DSSE/SSHSIG substrate; the\n  trusted service (ee0b) and its IaC; any trusted-env policy change.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Dependency gate: the asymmetric producer path is verified present before any removal — an\n      import check plus an end-to-end op-cert sign/verify smoke test pass on the branch this\n      story builds on; recorded as the story's first verification step.\n- [ ] A test asserts no code path signs an HMAC operation-cert: the `plan-review` /\n      `completion-verifier` kinds no longer resolve the `HMAC-SHA256` scheme in\n      `registry.POLICY`, and `signing.sign_manifest` has no HMAC branch reachable for these\n      kinds (`compute_signature` and `.signing-key` remain for non-op-cert consumers).\n- [ ] A test asserts no code path ACCEPTS an HMAC operation-cert: a pre-existing HMAC-signed\n      attestation for either kind reads as not-certified post-contract (preserved in the log,\n      never rewritten), and re-running the gate re-issues a valid Ed25519 op-cert on the same\n      ticket.\n- [ ] `docs/migrations/hmac-opcert-removal.md` exists, is non-empty, and contains `## Expand` and\n      `## Contract` sections plus the cutover (upgrade-order) and re-issue procedures; a test\n      asserts existence, non-emptiness, and both section headings.\n- [ ] The authorship kind (`rebar.authorship.v1`) and any non-op-cert HMAC consumer are untouched;\n      a test asserts authorship verification still passes post-removal.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` green."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784005149756507001,"uuid":"7e4e1f76-ebe9-4831-be7c-83deb7a97cca"}